name: bell pepper production, open field | bell pepper | Cutoff, U
description:
ecoQuery: https://ecoquery.ecoinvent.org/3.10/cutoff/dataset/21668/documentation

This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of fresh bell peppers in an irrigated open field. ;The LCA study, from which this LCI has been derived, contains detailed descriptions of the system boundaries and the data sources used (Stoessel et al. 2012). The publication is published and freely available with comprehensive supporting information:;http://pubs.acs.org/doi/pdf/10.1021/es2030577;Franziska Stoessel, Ronnie Juraske, Stephan Pfister, Stefanie Hellweg. (2012) Life Cycle Inventory and Carbon and Water FoodPrint of Fruits and Vegetables: Application to a Swiss Retailer. Environmental Science & Technology 6(46) 3253-3262.;;This activity was adapted to include the global average land use change (LUC) emissions according 2nd edition of the Quantis-modified tool developed by Blonk Consultants 'WFLDB-adapted-Blonk 2014 direct-land-use-change-assessment-tool_2015-05-18a.xlsx', tab. 'Country & land use unknown'. The size of the emission depends on (i) the relative crop expansion in all countries of the crop during the last 20 years and (ii) the corresponding, country specific land transformations. The current results are based on the average FAOSTAT data (harvested area) of 2009-2011 and 1989-1991. The weighted average is used which takes into account relative difference in crop expansion into primary forest, secondary forest, grassland, perennial and annual land.;[This dataset is meant to replace the following datasets:]

This activity starts about four weeks after the harvest of the previous crop. The soil is prepared for cultivation in mid- September and sowing was done about five months after soil preparation. Thereafter the crop is mature for harvesting in about 5 months.


The activity ends with the harvesting of the mature Capsicum from the Capsicum plant
category: A:Agriculture, forestry and fishing/01:Crop and animal production, hunting and related service activities/012:Growing of perennial crops/0128:Growing of spices, aromatic, drug and pharmaceutical crops

processDocumentation.timeDescription: Soil cultivating date for the main crop: 15-September, 2015; Harvesting date main crop: 16-July, 2016. The soil cultivation, sowing and harvesting dates are taken as the middle date of the week or fortnight told to the data collector by the farmer. Total time from date of sowing to date of harvesting comes to 153 days.  The data is collected for one crop cycle. The cycle of one year is considered for entry in ecoeditor.
processDocumentation.technologyDescription: Cultivation of Capsicum follows conventional production standards
processDocumentation.dataTreatmentDescription: The dataset is extrapolated from the respective regional datasets present in the database. Uncertainty has been adjusted accordingly.
processDocumentation.samplingDescription: The dataset is a weighted average from the respective regional datasets.

Fertiliser/s used in this dataset is/are: 'lime', 'nitrogen fertiliser, as N', 'phosphate fertiliser, as P2O5', 'phosphate rock, as P2O5, beneficiated, dry', 'potassium chloride, as K2O', 'potassium sulfate, as K2O', 'urea, as N'. The total amount of active substance/s is doubled in order to account for the packaging of the dilluted product of fertiliser/s that is/are applied. Therefore, 1.77E-01 kg of packaging for fertilisers is justified with this exchange.

exchanges.description: Calculated value based on literature. The gross energy is calculated using following formula; gross energy (MJ) = crude protein (kg)*23.04 (MJ/kg)+crude fat (kg)*38.96 (MJ/kg)+crude fibre (kg)*17.95 (MJ/kg)+carbohydrates (kg)*17.17 (MJ/kg) (formula based on expert opinion, cross referenced; Diepenbrock, 2012, Energy Balance in Crop Production). The product composition of fruits and vegetables is extracted from the USDA National Nutrient Database for Standard Reference (http://ndb.nal.usda.gov/, accessed 20131114). Crude protein (g)= 8.6, crude fat (g)= 1.7, crude fibre (g)= 17, ash (g)= 4.3, water (g)= 938.9, carbohydrates (g)= 46.4. The gross energy per kg of DM is 19.24MJ. The calculated gross energy per kg of reference product is thus 1.59MJ.
